\section{Agent \& Review Configuration}

\begin{frame}{Agent Configuration Strategy}
    GitHub Copilot uses a file-based configuration to define "Who" the AI is and "How" it behaves.
    \vspace{0.5cm}
    \begin{columns}[t]
        \column{0.5\textwidth}
        \textbf{1. The Global Persona (Root)}
        \begin{itemize}
            \item File: \texttt{AGENTS.md}
            \item Role: Defines the baseline "MedTech Developer".
            \item Scope: Applies to the whole repo.
        \end{itemize}

        \column{0.5\textwidth}
        \textbf{2. The Reviewer (Guardrails)}
        \begin{itemize}
            \item File: \texttt{.github/copilot-instructions.md}
            \item Role: "Quality Gatekeeper".
            \item Scope: Applies during Pull Requests.
        \end{itemize}
    \end{columns}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}[fragile]{Artifact: The Agent Definition}
    \textbf{File:} \texttt{AGENTS.md}
    \begin{lstlisting}[language=markdown, caption={Defining the Safety Constraints}]
---
name: "Safety Critical Firmware Agent"
tools: [pytest, mypy, grep]
---
# Mission
You are an expert in IEC 62304 Class C software. 
Your code must be defensive and strictly typed.

# Constraints
1. **Precision:** NEVER use standard float. Use `decimal.Decimal`.
2. **Traceability:** ALWAYS annotate functions with `@trace("REQ-ID")`.
3. **Safety:** If unsure about a calculation, STOP and ask.
    \end{lstlisting}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Scalability: How Many Agents?}
    There is \textbf{no hard limit} on the number of agents.
    \vspace{0.5cm}
    \begin{description}
        \item[Task-Specific Fleet] Located in \texttt{.github/agents/*.md}. You can have distinct agents for \textit{Security}, \textit{QA}, \textit{Documentation}, etc.
        \item[Context-Specific] Located in subdirectories (e.g., \texttt{src/ui/AGENTS.md}). These override global rules for specific folders.
    \end{description}
\end{frame}

